<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="148" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,911,1536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1245,1270]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Was" authorityName="Was" box="[321,591,1245,1270]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lifouensis">
<emphasis box="[321,540,1245,1270]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Epigonus lifouensis</emphasis>
Was
</taxonomicName>
originally described on the basis of tWo specimens collected from the south of Lifou Island, 
<collectingRegion box="[338,516,1278,1303]" country="New Caledonia" name="Province des Iles" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">Loyalty Islands</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[530,707,1278,1303]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">NeW Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, at depths of 
<quantity box="[864,993,1278,1303]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.375" metricValueMax="5.75" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" unit="m" value="537.5" valueMax="575.0" valueMin="500.0">500–575 m</quantity>
and recogniZed as a member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goode &amp; Bean" baseAuthorityYear="1881" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pandionis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">E. pandionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (Okamoto &amp; Motomura 2013). The present specimen represents the first record of the species from the South 
<collectingCountry box="[330,397,1345,1370]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">China</collectingCountry>
Sea, 
<collectingCountry box="[461,547,1345,1370]" name="Taiwan" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">TaiWan</collectingCountry>
. DeepWater cardinalfishes of 
<collectingCountry box="[884,966,1345,1370]" name="Taiwan" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">TaiWan</collectingCountry>
are represented by tWo species including the first record of 
<taxonomicName box="[358,498,1378,1403]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lifouensis">
<emphasis box="[358,498,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">E. lifouensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
here reported and 
<taxonomicName authority="DieuZeide, 1950" authorityName="DieuZeide" authorityYear="1950" box="[712,1078,1378,1403]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="denticulatus">
<emphasis box="[712,882,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">E. denticulatus</emphasis>
DieuZeide, 1950
</taxonomicName>
. Although Gon (2000) listed 
<taxonomicName authority="(Brauer 1906)" authorityName="Brauer" authorityYear="1906" baseAuthorityName="Brauer" baseAuthorityYear="1906" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">E. macrops</emphasis>
(Brauer 1906)
</taxonomicName>
in the checklist of the fishes of the South 
<collectingCountry box="[916,983,1412,1437]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="148">China</collectingCountry>
Sea, it may be a misidentification (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,487,1445,1470]" pageId="7" pageNumber="148" refId="ref5852" refString="OKAmOTO, M. &amp; NAKAyAmA, N. (2016) FIRsT REcORds Of THE lumInOus dEEPWATER cARdInAlfIsH (PERcIfORmEs: EPIgOnIdAE), Epigonus macrops (BRAuER, 1906), fROm THE sOuTHEAsTERn ATlAnTIc And TImOR SEA. Species Diversity, 21, 79 - 83." type="journal article">Okamoto &amp; Nakayama 2016</bibRefCitation>
). It should be noted that the specimens available to date Were collected at a ridge nearby remote islands or a seamount rather than on the continental slope, suggesting a particular habitat of the species.
</paragraph>
